(951, 2454722, 2454722, '20:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Days', 1, 'RESURRECTION: Written and Performed by Daniel Beaty; Directed by Oz Scott ', '&lt;em&gt;September 12 -13, 2008&lt;br /&gt;8pm and Broadway Performance Hall&lt;br /&gt;1625 Broadway; Seattle, WA &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;CD Forum Session! A post performance Q &amp; A free to ticket holders Sept. 12th and 13th.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&quot;Daniel Beaty is a new voice in American theatre celebrated as &amp;ldquo;compassionate and precise.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;- The New York Times&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Daniel Beaty, the 2007 &lt;a href=&quot;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Obie_award&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Obie&lt;/a&gt; Award Winner for Outstanding Writing and Performance for &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://danielbeaty.com/projects.html&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Emergence-SEE!&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;, is back in Seattle with his powerful new work: &lt;strong&gt;RESURRECTION&lt;/strong&gt;. Featuring Daniel&amp;rsquo;s unique blend of music, poetry, comedy and drama, &lt;strong&gt;RESURRECTION &lt;/strong&gt;follows six interconnected men, ages 10 through 60&amp;mdash;a child scientist, a young man from the projects preparing for college, an ex-convict, an executive, and a Bishop of a mega-church&amp;mdash;through an evening that changes their lives forever.  The stories of these African American men collide one evening in an unforgettable look at identity, relationships and, above all, our human connections. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Tickets:&lt;/strong&gt; $20/$15 for CD Forum members/students/seniors &lt;br /&gt;Order online at &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/37158&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;www.BrownPaperTickets.com&lt;/a&gt; or call 1-800-838-3006. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Media sponsor KUOW 94.9 Public Radio ', 1, 2, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
(952, 2454851, 2454851, '00:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'A Staged Reading of Experts of Martin Luther King Jr.’s Speeches ', 'Arranged and Directed&lt;br /&gt;by Gin Hammond&lt;br /&gt;Part of the Seattle Center&amp;rsquo;s Annual Martin Luther King Jr. People&amp;rsquo;s Celebration&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;Monday, January 19, 2009, Time- TBD&lt;br /&gt;The Center House Pavilion/Seattle Center; Seattle, WA&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;From &lt;em&gt;I Have a Dream&lt;/em&gt; to &lt;em&gt;Beyond Vietnam,&lt;/em&gt; Martin Luther King Jr.&amp;rsquo;s words are revolutionary in the face of opposition. Dr. King&amp;rsquo;s speeches are powerful, inspiring and controversial and spanned issues from civil and global human rights to nuclear proliferation. Join the CD Forum and the Seattle Center as we celebrate the power and depth of those words in honor of Dr. King&amp;rsquo;s birthday.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;This event is free and open to the public. ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[9X', ''),
(953, 2454862, 2454863, '20:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Guillermo E. Brown and BiLLLL$ Shuffle Mode ', '&lt;em&gt;CD Forum Session! A post performance Q &amp; A free to ticket holders&lt;br /&gt;January 30th &amp; 31st.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Friday and Saturday, January 30-31, 2009&lt;br /&gt;8pm at Broadway Performance Hall&lt;br /&gt;1625 Broadway; Seattle, WA &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&amp;ldquo;Shuffle Mode&quot; is pure Guillermo E. Brown, a masterful performing artist who is called a &amp;ldquo;musical omnivore.&quot;&lt;/em&gt; all about jazz.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Imagine an artist forcing all his sonic possibilities into an hour-long spectacle of music and video.  Guillermo E. Brown&amp;rsquo;s &lt;em&gt;Shuffle Mode&lt;/em&gt;&amp;mdash;an experimental, beat-based, electronic, jazzy, soulful, label-free, multimedia work tracing one man&amp;rsquo;s pathway to music through a diversity of influences is that. Like a broken iPod, &lt;em&gt;Shuffle Mode&lt;/em&gt; is intentionally glitchy, providing no clear-cut answers but erasing, through its very existence, false boundaries, jumping erratically between genres and conjuring the very spirit of modern music. Brown uses live instrumentation, backed by electronic arrangements and video. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Tickets: &lt;/strong&gt;$20/$15 for students/seniors&lt;br /&gt;Order online at &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/37475&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;www.BrownPaperTickets.com&lt;/a&gt; or call 1-800-838-3006.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Media Sponsor KUOW 94.9 Public Radio ', 2, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[3X', ''),
(954, 2454967, 2454967, '20:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Days', 1, 'Dance Split Bill with Camille A. Brown and Makeda Thomas ', '&lt;em&gt;Friday and Saturday, May 15-16, 2009 &lt;br /&gt;8pm at Broadway Performance Hall&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;1625 Broadway; Seattle, WA &lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;CD Forum Session! A post performance Q &amp; A free to ticket holders May 15th &amp; 16th. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Dance split bill featuring work by Camille A. Brown and the US Premiere of Makeda Thomas&amp;rsquo; new solo work &lt;em&gt;FreshWater,&lt;/em&gt; co-commissioned by the CD Forum.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.myspace.com/camie_cam&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Camille A. Brown&amp;rsquo;s&lt;/a&gt; choreography is a &amp;ldquo;tour de force&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;reveals&amp;rdquo; an arresting individuality as both choreographer and performer.  Her work focuses on combining elements of both contemporary and West African movement to dialogue about issues pertaining to the human spirit and its often deep, enlightening, and even humorous journey through life. Ms. Brown has received commissions from Hubbard Street II, Urban Bush Women, Ailey II, among others. She received the Princess Grass Award in Choreography, a New York Foundation for the Arts Grant, and the Presidential Scholar in the Arts Award in Dance. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://makedathomas.org/default.aspx&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Makeda Thomas&lt;/a&gt; choreographs works that cross boundaries between contemporary modern and traditional dance.  &lt;em&gt;Fresh Water &lt;/em&gt;takes its title from the Trinidadian term for someone who talks, dresses or acts American without having gone overseas (crossing salt water). The term also serves to remind someone who may have indeed gone overseas that they are still Caribbean. Created in the midst of returning home to Trinidad after 20 years living abroad, it is a deeply personal work. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Tickets:&lt;/strong&gt; $20/$15 for students/seniors &lt;br /&gt;Order online at &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/37210&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;www.BrownPaperTickets.com&lt;/a&gt; or call 1-800-838-3006. ', 1, 2, 0, 0, 0, '0[3X', ''),
(955, 2454763, 2454763, '19:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Which Way Seattle? Series: Black Elected Officials ', '&lt;em&gt;Thursday, October 23, 2008&lt;br /&gt;7pm at Pigott Auditorium &amp;ndash; Seattle University&lt;br /&gt;900 Broadway; Seattle, WA &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Which Way Seattle? is an ongoing series of civic dialogues about local and political affairs that directly impact Seattle&amp;rsquo;s African-American community.  The CD Forum is pleased to host a timely panel discussing black elected officials and their impact on their constituents, specifically the Black community.  We will explore whether or not Black representation makes a difference in the many issues faced in our community and address how racial politics impact a candidate&amp;rsquo;s platform. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Tickets:&lt;/strong&gt; $7/$5 for students/seniors  &lt;br /&gt;Order online at &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/37201&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;www.BrownPaperTickets.com&lt;/a&gt; or call 1-800-838-3006.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;Media Sponsor KBCS 91.3&lt;/em&gt; ', 1, 2, 0, 0, 0, '0[9X', ''),
(956, 2454805, 2454805, '19:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'American Heritage Series: Afro-Mexico ', 'Co-sponsored by Northwest African American Museum&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;Thursday, December 4, 2008&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;7pm at the Northwest African American Museum&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;2300 South Massachusetts St.; Seattle, WA&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;American Heritage &lt;/strong&gt;is an ongoing series of lectures and discussions that offer new perspectives on the role of African-Americans in American History. This is the first installment dealing with the &lt;a href=&quot;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/African_diaspora&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;African diaspora&lt;/a&gt;.The African presence in Mexico is rarely recognized or wildly known. Two hundred years before the United States abolished slavery, a community of free Blacks was established in the 1600&amp;rsquo;s in what is now Veracruz, Mexico. As a result, issues of nationalism, color and race are integral to the discussion of what it means to be Mexican. Join the CD Forum and a panel of experts as we discuss historical and contemporary issues of &lt;a href=&quot;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Afromestizos&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Afromestizo&lt;/a&gt; identity. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Tickets:&lt;/strong&gt; $7/$5 for students/seniors  &lt;br /&gt;Order online at &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/37204%20or%20call%201-800-838-3006&quot;&gt;www.BrownPaperTickets.com&lt;/a&gt; or call 1-800-838-3006.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;Media Sponsor KBCS 91.3&lt;/em&gt; ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[9X', ''),
(957, 2454882, 2454882, '19:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Which Way Seattle? Series: The Black Face of Hip-hop ', 'Co-sponsored by the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.myspace.com/dope_emporium&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Dope Emporium&lt;/a&gt; &lt;em&gt;Thursday February 19, 2009 &lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;7pm at Langston Hughes Performing Arts Center&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;104 17th Ave. S (Near Yesler); &lt;/em&gt;&lt;em&gt;Seattle, WA &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Which Way Seattle? is an ongoing series of civic dialogues about local and political affairs that directly impact Seattle&amp;rsquo;s African-American community. Hip-Hop has deep roots in Seattle and the Northwest. Black Hip-Hop artists have pioneered and set the groundwork for many Northwest Hip-Hop artists. Does this history relate to the present representation and influence of Black people in the Hip-Hop industry?  Is there a &amp;ldquo;political narrowness&amp;rdquo; around the dialogue of race and Hip-Hop and the view of what is &amp;ldquo;conscious&amp;rdquo; Hip-Hop? Join us as we address these complex issues and recognize the roots of Hip-Hop in Seattle.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Tickets:&lt;/strong&gt; $5/ FREE for students/seniors  &lt;br /&gt;Order online at &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/37207&quot;&gt;www.BrownPaperTickets.com&lt;/a&gt; or call 1-800-838-3006.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;Media Sponsor KBCS 91.3&lt;/em&gt; ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[9X', ''),
(958, 2454938, 2454938, '19:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'American Heritage Series: Caribbean Americans ', 'Co-sponsored by Northwest African American Museum&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Thursday, April 16, 2009&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;7pm at the Northwest African American Museum&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;2300 South Massachusetts St.; Seattle, WA &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;American Heritage &lt;/strong&gt;is an ongoing series of lectures and discussions that offer new perspectives on the role of African-Americans in American History. Over five million Americans are of Caribbean ancestry, from &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.marcusgarvey.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Marcus Garvey&lt;/a&gt; to &lt;a href=&quot;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DJ_Kool_Herc&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;DJ Kool Herc&lt;/a&gt;, Black Caribbean&amp;rsquo;s have made significant contributions to American history and culture. Please join us as we celebrate and acknowledge these political and cultural contributions. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Tickets:&lt;/strong&gt; $7/$5 for students/seniors  &lt;br /&gt;Order online at &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/37208&quot;&gt;www.BrownPaperTickets.com&lt;/a&gt; or call 1-800-838-3006.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;Media Sponsor KBCS 91.3&lt;/em&gt; ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[9X', ''),
