(986, 2454729, 2454735, '19:15:00', '23:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'The Universe Of Keith Haring ', '&lt;p&gt;SEPTEMBER 19 &amp;ndash; 25, FRIDAY &amp;ndash; THURSDAY AT 7:15, 9:15PM              (PLUS SATURDAY &amp; SUNDAY AT 5:15PM)&lt;/p&gt;          &lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/41783&quot;&gt;The Universe Of Keith Haring&lt;/a&gt;     Sponsored by &lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.vital5productions.com/projects/thehideout.html&quot;&gt;THE HIDEOUT BAR&lt;/a&gt;     (Christina Clausen, USA, 2007, digiBETA, 90 min)     &lt;br /&gt;     &lt;p&gt; The creator of some of the most popular and enduring images of late 20th Century art, Keith Haring was also an iconic figure of the downtown New York scene in the &amp;rsquo;80s. Christina Clausen&amp;rsquo;s documentary offers an affectionate, deeply personal glimpse into Haring&amp;rsquo;s life, from his early years growing up in a small, conservative Pennsylvania town to his heyday as a world&amp;ndash;renowned artist, rubbing shoulders with the likes of Madonna, Jean&amp;ndash;Michel Basquiat, and Andy Warhol. Haring&amp;rsquo;s family and childhood friends offer anecdotes about the artist&amp;rsquo;s early years, but it is the recollections of the &amp;rsquo;70&amp;rsquo;s and &amp;rsquo;80s New York art scene that form the heart and soul of this documentary. Combining music of the era, photo stills, and audio interviews, Clausen brings the sights and sounds of these decades vividly to life. Yoko Ono, Junior Vasquez, David LaChappelle, and gallery owner Tony Shafrazi are among those who offer insight into the significance of Haring&amp;rsquo;s work, as well as their personal memories of their friendship with him. &lt;/p&gt;     &lt;br /&gt;          &lt;img src=&quot;http://www.nwfilmforum.org/images/calendar/fall08/haring.jpg&quot; /&gt; &lt;em&gt;&lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/41783&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.nwfilmforum.org/images/buytickets.gif&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;           &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;MORE INFO AT WWW.NWFILMFORUM.ORG ', 7, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
(987, 2454728, 2454728, '20:00:00', '22:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'DOXITA ', '&lt;p&gt;SEPTEMBER 18, THURSDAY AT 8PM&lt;/p&gt;          &lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/41785&quot;&gt;Doxita&lt;/a&gt;          &lt;br /&gt;     &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;&gt; Doxita is a traveling festival of documentary films that are under 40 minutes in length. The program, comprised of approximately two hours of film, represents a wide variety of documentary designed to profile the great content and artistic vision that non&amp;ndash;fiction short films provide, but that people don&amp;rsquo;t often get a chance to see. The festival includes Martin Thomas (A film about one´s man´s painful journey to stop his stammer, UK/Wales, by Dylan Wyn Thomas, 31 minutes); The Guarantee (A tale told through animated drawings of one man´s consideration of plastic surgery to help his ballet career, USA, by Jesse Epstein, 10 minutes); Cross Your Eyes, Keep Them Wide (An invitation into a special workspace for artists with development disabilities; USA, by Ben Wu, 23 minutes); El Cerco (A breathtaking look at tuna fishing in the Mediterranean, Spain, by Ricardo Iscar/Nacho Martin, 12 minutes); and Vángelo Monzón (An inside look at a man who has been making bricks in Argentina since he was a boy, Sweden, by Andréas Lennartsson, 8 minutes), among others.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;&gt;More info at www.nwfilmforum.org&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
(988, 2454735, 2454735, '20:00:00', '22:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'You&#039;re Lookin&#039; At Country ', '&lt;p&gt;SEPTEMBER 25, THURSDAY AT 8PM&lt;/p&gt;          &lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/41817&quot;&gt;You&amp;rsquo;re Lookin&amp;rsquo; at Country&lt;/a&gt;     Sponsored by &lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://kbcs.fm/site/PageServer&quot;&gt;KBCS 91.3 FM&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt; Vintage performance footage from the &quot;Golden Era of Country Music&quot; and a live performance by singer/songwriter and Sirius Radio &amp;ldquo;Outlaw Country&amp;rdquo; DJ Dallas Wayne      &lt;br /&gt;     &lt;p&gt; Join us for a rollicking second edition of You&amp;rsquo;re Lookin&amp;rsquo; at Country, featuring rarely seen footage of country music giants in their heyday, narrated by Texas troubadour and celebrated Sirius Radio &amp;ldquo;Outlaw Country&amp;rdquo; DJ, Dallas Wayne. Wayne will transport you to a bygone era filled with big hair, Nudie suits, jamborees, and cheerful songs about alcoholism, despair, family feuds, murder, and couples in trouble. This program will feature such greats as Hank, George, Porter, Johnny, Willie, Buck, and Loretta, singing a blissful mix of high lonesome and down dirty. The film presentation will be followed by a short live performance by Wayne, whose songs will not only take you back to the glory days of country music, but also give you hope for its future. Refreshments available. &lt;/p&gt;     &lt;br /&gt;     &lt;p&gt;Tickets $10/NWFF members, $12/general&lt;/p&gt;     &lt;br /&gt;     &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;ldquo;Wayne has one of the best honky&amp;ndash;tonk voices in America today... If Nashville still valued grit and twang this guy would be a major star.&amp;rdquo; &amp;ndash;Radney Foster, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.purespunk.com/&quot;&gt;www.purespunk.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;     &lt;br /&gt;     &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;ldquo;Missouri&amp;ndash;born Dallas Wayne is to hardcore honky&amp;ndash;tonk what 100 proof corn whisky is to hard liquor. Wayne&amp;rsquo;s sterling originals shine with exquisit hillbilly wit and poetry.&amp;rdquo; Bob Allen, &lt;a href=&quot;http://sonicnet.com/&quot;&gt;sonicnet.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;     &lt;br /&gt;          &lt;img src=&quot;http://www.nwfilmforum.org/images/calendar/fall08/country1.jpg&quot; /&gt;  &lt;em&gt;&lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/41817&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.nwfilmforum.org/images/buytickets.gif&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;MORE INFO AT WWW.NWFILMFORUM.ORG&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/em&gt; ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[3X', ''),
(989, 2454743, 2454749, '00:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'LOCAL SIGHTINGS FILM FESTIVAL ', '&lt;p&gt;OCTOBER 3 &amp;ndash; 9 &lt;/p&gt;          &lt;a target=&quot;_self&quot; href=&quot;http://www.localsightings.org/&quot;&gt;Local Sightings&lt;/a&gt;               &lt;br /&gt;     &lt;p&gt; Local Sightings is a film festival for the Northwest.&lt;/p&gt;     &lt;br /&gt;     &lt;p&gt;Northwest Film Forum&amp;rsquo;s premiere showcase of Northwest filmmaking is back, bigger than ever. The festival, which happens at NWFF&amp;rsquo;s theaters in Seattle, features great prizes, filmmaker parties, archival Northwest films and an impressive national film industry jury looking for strong Northwest work.&lt;/p&gt;     &lt;br /&gt;     &lt;p&gt;The annual festival includes both feature film presentations as well as short film programs and special events with live film performances, installation art, audience participation and parties. This year&amp;rsquo;s festival takes place in the cinemas of Northwest Film Forum from October 3&amp;ndash;8. The line up of films will be announced and posted on the website on September 20. Included in this year&amp;rsquo;s festival will be the usual assortment of fiction, documentary and experimental films as well as a featured presentation of a historical Seattle film, a staged reading of this year&amp;rsquo;s Washington State Screenplay Competition winning script, and an opening party that will ignite Seattle&amp;rsquo;s film scene Friday night and keep it bleary eyed Saturday morning.&lt;/p&gt;     &lt;br /&gt;          &lt;img src=&quot;http://www.nwfilmforum.org/images/calendar/fall08/localsightings.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;MORE INFO AT www.localsightings.org ', 7, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
(990, 2454771, 2454771, '19:00:00', '21:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Halloween Thriller Party ', '&lt;p&gt;OCTOBER 31, FRIDAY AT 7PM &lt;/p&gt;          &lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/42082&quot;&gt;Halloween Thriller Party &lt;/a&gt;     Free For Members!&lt;br /&gt;       Special 25th Anniversary Celebration!     &lt;br /&gt;     &lt;p&gt; Before you hit the Halloween parties, join us for a celebration of the epic music video that created a phenomenon and made Michael Jackson the &amp;ldquo;King Of Pop!&amp;rdquo; It was 25 years ago that Jackson enlisted director John Landis to make the long&amp;ndash;form horror&amp;ndash;themed video for the title song of his record&amp;ndash;breaking hit album. For this special event, we present a special screening of the classic video (featuring the best zombie choreography ever captured on film!) as well as the rarely seen hour&amp;ndash;long TV special The Making Of Michael Jackson&amp;rsquo;s Thriller including behind&amp;ndash;the&amp;ndash;scenes footage (showing Jackson&amp;rsquo;s fascination with facial transformation), interviews with young fans (&amp;ldquo;He&amp;rsquo;s so sexy!&amp;rdquo;), and his other videos and performances. We&amp;rsquo;ll also have music and drinks in the cinema. Horror legend Vincent Price comments, &amp;ldquo;no mere mortal can resist the evil of the thriller,&amp;rdquo; adding &amp;ldquo;Aah ha ha ha ha ha ha&amp;ndash; AAHH HA Ha ha ha&amp;hellip; &amp;rdquo; Be there!&lt;/p&gt;     &lt;br /&gt;          &lt;img src=&quot;http://www.nwfilmforum.org/images/calendar/fall08/thriller.jpg&quot; /&gt; &lt;em&gt;&lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/42082&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.nwfilmforum.org/images/buytickets.gif&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;More info at www.nwfilmforum.org&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/em&gt; ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[9X', ''),
(991, 2454775, 2454775, '20:00:00', '22:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Election Evening Extravaganza! ', '&lt;p&gt;NOVEMBER 4, TUESDAY AT 8PM&lt;/p&gt;          &lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/42334&quot;&gt;Election Evening Extravaganza&lt;/a&gt;     &lt;br /&gt;     &lt;p&gt; Don&amp;rsquo;t let your Champagne go flat this election night! Join Northwest Film Forum and Strawberry Theatre Workshop as we turn NWFF into the epicenter of election information, complete with major network broadcasts, radio coverage, a &amp;ldquo;Capitol Hill Petting Zoo&amp;rdquo; with a donkey and an elephant, and live blogging all night long! As each state gets called, watch our master of ceremonies post red and blue light bulbs on our giant map of the country, marking wins for Obama or McCain. Raise a glass in celebration or dilute your beer with your tears&amp;ndash;either way, it beats being home and yelling at your television. The Extravaganza is a fund&amp;ndash;raising party for Northwest Film Forum and Strawberry Theatre Workshop. Suggested donation $10. &lt;/p&gt;     &lt;br /&gt;          &lt;img src=&quot;http://www.nwfilmforum.org/images/calendar/fall08/election.jpg&quot; /&gt;  &lt;em&gt;&lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/42334&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.nwfilmforum.org/images/buytickets.gif&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;        &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;MORE INFO AT www.nwfilmforum.org ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[9X', ''),
(992, 2454792, 2454798, '19:00:00', '21:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Obscene: A Portrait of Barney Rosset and Grove Press ', '&lt;p&gt;NOVEMBER 21 &amp;ndash; 26, FRIDAY &amp;ndash; WEDNESDAY AT 7, 9PM &lt;/p&gt;          &lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/42095&quot;&gt;Obscene: A Portrait of Barney Rosset and Grove Press&lt;/a&gt;         Sponsored by &lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.aclu-wa.org/&quot;&gt;ACLU of Washington&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt; (Daniel O&amp;rsquo;Connor, Neil Ortenberg, USA, 2007, BetaSP, 97 min)     &lt;br /&gt;     &lt;p&gt;Although it is likely you&amp;rsquo;ve never heard of Barney Rosset, he is one of the most influential cultural figures of the 20th century. Through his imprint Grove Press and his magazine Evergreen Review, Rosset fought tooth and nail (often before state and federal supreme courts) for the American right to read the works of Samuel Beckett Henry Miller, Jean Genet, Jack Kerouac, William S. Burroughs, Harold Pinter, D H Lawrence, Alain Robbe&amp;ndash;Grillet, Amiri Baraka and many other &amp;ldquo;enemies of morality&amp;rdquo;. &amp;ldquo;Grove was a valve for pressurized cultural energies,&amp;rdquo; says the now octogenarian and still feisty Rosset, &amp;ldquo;a breach in the dam of American Puritanism.&amp;rdquo; Obscene traces the important history and impact of Groove&amp;rsquo;s free speech fights &amp;mdash; from Ginsburg&amp;rsquo;s &amp;ldquo;Howl&amp;rdquo; to &amp;ldquo;The Autobiography of Malcolm X&amp;rdquo; to the Swedish film I Am Curious (Yellow) &amp;mdash; while creating a fascinating portrait of the volatile, eccentric Rosset whose unyielding restless energy and questionable business sense upended both this country&amp;rsquo;s censorship law and his own life.&lt;/p&gt;     &lt;br /&gt;          &lt;img src=&quot;http://www.nwfilmforum.org/images/calendar/fall08/obscene-barney.jpg&quot; /&gt;  &lt;em&gt;&lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/42095&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.nwfilmforum.org/images/buytickets.gif&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;More info at www.nwfilmforum.org&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/em&gt; ', 7, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
