(1492, 2454944, 2454944, '20:00:00', '23:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'QUEER FILM NIGHT SEATTLE! ', '&lt;font size=&quot;2&quot; style=&quot;style&quot;&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#6600ff&quot; style=&quot;style&quot;&gt;Every other week we will be screening a different film from the ever expanding list of queer films. The good, the bad, and the ugly. Do movies look different through a bent lens? Come join us as we explore film from a queer perspective. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#ff0000&quot; style=&quot;style&quot;&gt;Films start at 8 PM. There&#039;s always popcorn, come early to help, OPEN TO EVERYONE, 2719 East John + corner street is MLK. E-mail sarine@aplacecalledyes.com for more info.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;2&quot; style=&quot;style&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;2&quot; color=&quot;#33cccc&quot; style=&quot;background-color:rgb(0,0,0);&quot;&gt;April 22: &lt;span style=&quot;font-family:helvetica;font-weight:bold;&quot;&gt;Paris Is Burning is a 1990 documentary film directed by Jennie Livingston. Filmed in the mid-to-late 1980s, it chronicles the ball culture of New York City and the poor, African American and Latino gay and transgendered community involved in it. Many consider Paris Is Burning to be an invaluable documentary of the end of the &quot;Golden Age&quot; of New York City drag balls, as well as a thoughtful exploration of race, class, and gender in America.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt; ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
