(1703, 2454989, 2454989, '10:00:00', '15:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Collective Voices Resisting Violence ', '&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(102,0,204);&quot;&gt;Saturday June 6th from 10am-3pm at Seattle Central Community College for a FREE conference:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:14pt;color:blue;&quot;&gt;Collective Voices Resisting Violence&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(102,0,204);&quot;&gt;This conference will include 8 sessions dealing with violence in its many forms and how different communities are affected by it. This isn&#039;t just a conversation about the violence that is happening but also a look in to the histories of oppressive forces on our communities and is an opportunity for us to come together to dialogue about it and work together for a better tomorrow. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;ldquo;This conversation is itself a form of activism; it&amp;rsquo;s our resistance to that idea of separation. We do have differences, but our commonalities are just as strong, and they represent hope for resistance and freedom.&amp;rdquo; &amp;ndash;bell hooks&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;RSVP:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;mailto:unitedpeoplescoalition@gmail.com&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;unitedpeoplescoalition@gmail.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(102,0,204);&quot;&gt;The sessions include:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1.&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight:normal;font-size:7pt;line-height:normal;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-size-adjust:none;font-stretch:normal;&quot;&gt;   &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10pt;&quot;&gt;The Movement for Non-Violence By Any Means Necessary Presented by Dr. Michael A. Tun&#039;cap, University of California, Berkeley.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:7pt;&quot;&gt;    &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10pt;&quot;&gt;                  This session is an introductory historical and comparative analysis of the African American, Chicano (Mexican American), Asian American, and American Indian Civil Rights Movements which emerged during the decade of the 1960s.  It offers an overview of the origins, ideologies, goals, strategies, and key organizations of those movements in the context of U.S. history and politics.  It critically examines the modern result and representation of the 21st century movement for non-violence.  We analyze the legacy of the Non-Violence movements to the present day struggles for an authentic multiracial, multiethnic, and multicultural democracy. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2.&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight:normal;font-size:7pt;line-height:normal;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-size-adjust:none;font-stretch:normal;&quot;&gt;   &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10pt;&quot;&gt;Community Organizing and the Quest for Racial Justice: A Chamoru Pedagogy. Presented by Dr. Michael A. Tun&amp;rsquo;cap, University of California, Berkeley &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(51,51,255);&quot;&gt;Develop an understanding of the Intersections between racial justice, ethnic studies and community organizing. This session will focus on alliance building between people of color, women and GBLT communities. The goal is to develop cross cultural communications skills that understand the possessive investment in whiteness and gender inequality. The group will explore the concept of decolonization and the Black Power and Civil Rights Movements and develop a critical consciousness for the intersections or race, gender, class and sexuality. How do we develop a multi-racial agenda and coalition of leaders for the 21st century?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3.&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight:normal;font-size:7pt;line-height:normal;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-size-adjust:none;font-stretch:normal;&quot;&gt;   &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10pt;&quot;&gt;Communities Against Rape and Abuse presents:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(0,102,0);&quot;&gt;In February of this year R&amp;B singer Chris Brown made national headlines when he was arrested for physically assaulting his girlfriend pop singer Rihanna. While the world had so much to say about their relationship, many in the African American community were silent. Domestic Violence affects all races and genders, but the intersection of racial interpersonal violence and racism affects our ability to respond to the violence in the lives of Black women. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4.&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight:normal;font-size:7pt;line-height:normal;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-size-adjust:none;font-stretch:normal;&quot;&gt;   &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10pt;&quot;&gt;Immigration/ Immigrant Rights Presented by SCCC Instructor Tracy        Lai&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(102,0,0);&quot;&gt;                  While the &lt;/span&gt;U.S.&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(102,0,0);&quot;&gt; is often thought of as a &amp;ldquo;nation of immigrants,&amp;rdquo;  the doors to immigration have not been open to everyone.  In this workshop, we can talk about the history of exclusion/discrimination, as well as current issues, such as immigration reform and the Dream Act (undocumented students).  &lt;/span&gt;Tracy&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(102,0,0);&quot;&gt; will bring copies of Underground Undergrads ($10 each for Seattle APALA), written by UCLA students and published by the &lt;/span&gt;UCLA Labor Center&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(102,0,0);&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;5.&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight:normal;font-size:7pt;line-height:normal;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-size-adjust:none;font-stretch:normal;&quot;&gt;   &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10pt;&quot;&gt;Woman of Color and State Violence Presented by Maria L. Guillen-Valdovinos. Associated Students of University of Washington, Women&amp;rsquo;s Action Commission Director.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(102,51,255);&quot;&gt;This workshop will address how state violence and the criminalization approach affect the lives of women of color within the Industrial Complex Prison System. In particular, we will examine how the prison system and detention centers function as violent institutions that bring many women into conflict with the law, particularly women of color, poor women, lesbians, sex workers, immigrant women, women with disabilities, and other marginalized women. We will discuss how we need to develop responses to gender violence that do not depend on a sexist, racist, classist, and homophobic criminal justice system while putting women in a system that is systematically violent and how violence in the lives of women of color within the prison system correlate with racism, patriarchy, and state power. We will also come up with strategies that challenged the criminal justice system and how we can participate in social justice movements that address and discus all forms of oppression.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;6.&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight:normal;font-size:7pt;line-height:normal;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-size-adjust:none;font-stretch:normal;&quot;&gt;     &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10pt;&quot;&gt;The Fourth World War: Film and Dialogue facilitated by the United Peoples Coalition&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(255,0,0);&quot;&gt;                  From the front-lines of conflicts in&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mexico&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(255,0,0);&quot;&gt;, &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Argentina&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(255,0,0);&quot;&gt;, &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;South Africa&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(255,0,0);&quot;&gt;, &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Palestine&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(255,0,0);&quot;&gt;, &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Korea&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(255,0,0);&quot;&gt;, and the North; from &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Seattle&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(255,0,0);&quot;&gt; to Genova, and the War on Terror in &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;New York&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(255,0,0);&quot;&gt;, &lt;/span&gt;Afghanistan&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(255,0,0);&quot;&gt;, and &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Iraq&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(255,0,0);&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;,&lt;/strong&gt; The Fourth World War is the story of men and women around the world who resist being annihilated in this war. While our airwaves are crowded with talk of a new world war, narrated by generals and filmed from the noses of bombs, the human story of this global conflict remains untold. This film brings together the images and voices of the war on the ground. It is a story of a war without end and of those who resist. This is a film that would have been unimaginable at any other moment in history. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;7.&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight:normal;font-size:7pt;line-height:normal;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-size-adjust:none;font-stretch:normal;&quot;&gt;     &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10pt;&quot;&gt;Seattle&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10pt;&quot;&gt; Central Community College&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10pt;&quot;&gt;&amp;rsquo;s Phi Theta Kappa Presents:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(0,102,0);&quot;&gt;This session will be a panel discussing homelessness in &lt;/span&gt;Seattle&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(0,102,0);&quot;&gt; and will include a Social Worker, Police Officer and Homeless Youth and will discuss their experiences. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;8.&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight:normal;font-size:7pt;line-height:normal;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-size-adjust:none;font-stretch:normal;&quot;&gt;     &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10pt;&quot;&gt;One Be Lo presents: Issues Around Islamaphobia &lt;br /&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(204,51,204);&quot;&gt;More info TBA&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;RSVP:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;mailto:unitedpeoplescoalition@gmail.com&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;unitedpeoplescoalition@gmail.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;&gt; &lt;strong&gt;This event is made possible by: &lt;/strong&gt;SCCC United Peoples Coalition,SCCC College Activities Board,Phi Theta Kappa: Alpha Chi Zeta,Communities Against Rape and Abuse (CARA),University of California, Berkeley&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[7X', ''),
(1660, 2454966, 2454966, '19:00:00', '21:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Speaking Tour: Andrej Grubacic, &quot;Anarchism for the 21st Century: Building Movements for Lasting Change&quot; ', '&lt;font&gt;&lt;font&gt;Common Action presents an evening with Andrej Grubacic, an anarchist historian from the Balkans, and author of &quot;Wobblies &amp; Zapatistas&quot;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font&gt;&lt;br /&gt; 			  &lt;font&gt;Thursday, May 14&lt;/font&gt;,                &lt;font&gt;7pm&lt;/font&gt; &lt;br /&gt;               &lt;br /&gt; 			  &lt;font&gt;2100 Building &lt;br /&gt;2100 24th Ave.&lt;br /&gt;Seattle, WA &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;font&gt; &lt;br /&gt;Andrej Grubacic is a radical historian -- or, more accurately, an anarchist historian -- from the Balkans. Formerly based in Belgrade, post-Yugoslavia, after many adventures and misadventures he found himself in Fernand Braudel Center at SUNY Binghamton. Andrej teaches at ZMedia Institute and most recently at the University of San Francisco. He has been part of many networks as an anarchist organizer (DSM!, Peoples Global Action, WSF, Freedom Fight, and many others). He is one of the founding members of the Global Balkans, a network of Balkan anti-capitalists in diaspora, and the ZBalkans, a Balkan edition of Z Magazine. Most recently he co-authored the book Wobblies and Zapatistas (PM Press, 2008) with Staughton Lynd. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;Presented by Common Action, a regional anarchist organization in the Northwest United States with members representing the cities of Seattle, Bremerton, Tacoma, and Olympia. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;Contact us at &lt;a href=&quot;mailto:nwcommonaction@gmail.com&quot;&gt;nwcommonaction@gmail.com&lt;/a&gt; or join the Common Action Announcements listserv at &lt;a href=&quot;http://groups.google.com/group/nwcommonactionannouncements&quot;&gt;http://groups.google.com/group/nwcommonactionannouncements&lt;/a&gt; for the occasional e-mail about sponsored events, publications, reports, and other fun stuff.&lt;/font&gt; &lt;br /&gt;             &lt;br /&gt; 			             &lt;font&gt;Website for more info:&lt;br /&gt;              &lt;/font&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nwcommonaction.org/&quot;&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#000099&quot;&gt;http://www.nwcommonaction.org&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/a&gt; ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[9X', ''),
