(1819, 2455043, 2455043, '00:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, '@ Arctic Circle ', '&lt;strong&gt;DEAD WESTERN&lt;/strong&gt; (Sacramento CA)&lt;br /&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.snailonastick.com/images/dead_western3.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Download/Listen at &lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.snailonastick.com/downloads.htm&quot;&gt;www.snailonastick.com/downloads.htm&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;or they have a MySpace at &lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.myspace.com/50690003&quot;&gt;www.myspace.com/50690003&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I think they&#039;re touring as a TRIO.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;ldquo;In shadow, he appears neanderthal; in light, he waxes angelic. Who is Dead Western? He is a man of a gaping mouth, out of which pours &amp;mdash; as readily as water from a faucet &amp;mdash; a haunting, bewildering, beautiful voice, reminiscent of Scott Walker (circa Climate of Hunter). This bellowing voice, like an ancient reptile, slithers and wraps itself around the most tender acoustic melodies. Dead Western sounds like a forest growing (the throatless groaning of age-old trees); feels like a Victorian passage through limbo (grey, ominous); looks like a Grecian statue (as drawn by Robert Crumb). This is the sort of music one feels profoundly acquainted with &amp;mdash; but not something generally found in record format. It is the shifting of rock, the scuttling of insects, the hissing of the wind: frightful, eternal.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;WEBELOS&lt;/strong&gt; (Seattle WA)&lt;br /&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2127/2101038055_eae8214a2e.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;They have a MySpace at &lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.myspace.com/thewebelosmusic&quot;&gt;www.myspace.com/thewebelosmusic&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Living Room Pop!&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;and &lt;strong&gt;WORLD HISTORY&lt;/strong&gt;!! &gt; &gt; &gt; - - - &gt; &lt;strong&gt;Seattle, WA&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;[clap your hands say &quot;daah&quot;]&lt;br /&gt; www.myspace.com/worldworldhistoryhistory&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;at the &lt;strong&gt;Arctic Circle&lt;/strong&gt; [Georgetown]&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.arcticcirclehouse.info/&quot;&gt;www.arcticcirclehouse.info&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;6633 Ellis Ave S [98108]--------&gt; #60. 131. 174 buses&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Bring $ for the bands.&lt;br /&gt;&amp; we&#039;ll have some food for you to eat.&lt;br /&gt;Food at 7:00PM&lt;br /&gt;Show at 8:00PM&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;IF YOU COME TO THE SHOW, Jamie&lt;br /&gt;(Seattle&#039;s Famous Comedian &amp; Winner of the World&#039;s Fastest Pancake Eater)&lt;br /&gt;will draw a quick portrait of you!!&lt;br /&gt; [you&#039;re gonna look soooooo gooooooooood]&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt; &lt;/strong&gt; ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[3X', ''),
(1820, 2455072, 2455078, '19:00:00', '21:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Burma VJ ', 'Normal   0   0   1   81   464   3   1   569   11.1282               0         0   0             &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;In 2007, over 100,000 protesters took to Burma&amp;rsquo;s streets, signaling the start of a rebellion against the nation&amp;rsquo;s oppressive dictatorship. As the government effectively shut down all media and communication in and out of the country, members of the Democratic Voice of Burma (DVB) braved the streets to film the rebellion as it unfolded. Their powerful footage was then smuggled into Thailand to be shared with the rest of the world. &lt;em&gt;Burma VJ&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt; is a gripping look at key moments caught on film by intrepid video journalists during this intense political struggle.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Northwest Film Forum&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;1515 12th Ave (between Pike &amp; Pine on Capitol Hill&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;www.nwfilmforum.org&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; ', 7, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
(1821, 2455079, 2455081, '19:00:00', '21:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Milestones ', '&lt;p&gt;            Normal   0   0   1   136   776   6   1   952   11.1282               0         0   0           &lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;  &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Milestones&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;(Robert Kramer, USA, 1975, 35mm, 195 min)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;After the Vietnam War, the American political left faced a surge in political conservatism that challenged their activist aspirations and ideals. &lt;em&gt;Milestones&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt; is an absorbing documentary that follows the stories of more than 50 of these Americans as they tried to express their radical beliefs in an increasingly stifling political environment. The spectrum of fascinating personal stories and contexts reflects the myriad of individuals and situations that gave rise to the New Left as a movement and social community in the 60s. &lt;em&gt;Milestones &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;is an eye-opening exploration of the hopes, dreams and lives that were affected by the weakening of a socio-political movement. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;ldquo;As a portrait of a sweet but slightly fractured man, it&amp;rsquo;s one of the most unexpectedly touching documentaries I&amp;rsquo;ve ever seen.&quot; &amp;mdash;Cinematical&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;SEPTEMBER 4&amp;ndash;7, FRIDAY&amp;ndash;MONDAY AT 7PM&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sponsored by KBCS 91.3 FM&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;NEW 35MM PRINT&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;p&gt;Northwest Film Forum&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;1515 12th Ave (between Pike &amp; Pine on Capitol Hill&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;www.nwfilmforum.org&lt;/p&gt; ', 3, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
(1822, 2455085, 2455085, '20:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Soul Nite! ', '&lt;p&gt;            Normal   0   0   1   61   352   2   1   432   11.1282               0         0   0             &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Soul Nite!&lt;br /&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;Soul Nite is back with electrifying &amp;lsquo;60s performances from Sam &amp; Dave, Joe Tex, Barbara Lynn, Marvin Gaye, The Temptations, Linda Carr, and a special set celebrating &lt;strong&gt;Otis Redding&amp;rsquo;s birthday!&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt; Everything from Motown smooth to Southern funky- live and in the raw, on the big screen and cranked up loud. Of course we&amp;rsquo;ll have beverages in the cinema, djs spinning soul platters, and dancing in the aisles is encouraged!&lt;span style=&quot;color:black;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Northwest Film Forum&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;1515 12th Ave (between Pike &amp; Pine on Capitol Hill&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;www.nwfilmforum.org&lt;/p&gt; ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[3X', ''),
(1823, 2455086, 2455088, '00:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Fierce Light: When Spirit Meets Action ', 'Normal   0   0   1   145   828   6   1   1016   11.1282               0         0   0             &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;SEPTEMBER 11&amp;ndash;13, FRIDAY&amp;ndash;SUNDAY AT 6:30PM (PLUS SAT&amp;ndash;SUN AT 3PM)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sponsored by KBCS 91.3 FM&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;SEATTLE PREMIERE&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;DIRECTOR IN ATTENDANCE&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Fierce light: When Spirit Meets Action&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;(Velcrow Ripper, Canada, 2009, Beta-SP, 90 min)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;An inspiring documentary about the global movement called spiritual activism, &lt;em&gt;Fierce Light &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;resonates with the compassion and open-mindedness of its subject matter. Acclaimed director Velcrow Ripper (&lt;em&gt;Scared Sacred&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;) interviews many of the movement&amp;rsquo;s illustrious figures, including Alice Walker, John Lewis, Daryl Hannah, Thich Nhat Hahn, Desmond Tutu, Julia Butterfly Hill and Noah Levine. These passionate leaders speak about their commitment to making positive change in the world, a belief shared by thousands across the globe. Their remarkable stories are accompanied by Ripper&amp;rsquo;s vivid imagery in his inspirational discovery of sincere human effort, love and activism.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;ldquo;Beautiful, poetic, powerful and important. Everyone (and I mean everyone) should see &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;Fierce Light&lt;em&gt;.&amp;rdquo; &amp;mdash;FFWD Magazine&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Northwest Film Forum&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;1515 12th Ave&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;www.nwfilmforum.org&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:11pt;font-family:&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; ', 3, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', '');
