(1847, 2455066, 2455066, '10:00:00', '12:01:00', 'Once', 0, 'Seattle Bicycle Music Festival ', 'The first annual &lt;a href=&quot;http://seattlebmf.org/&quot;&gt;Seattle Bicycle Music Festival&lt;/a&gt; occurs on Saturday. The BMF is a free bicycle powered music festival promoting sustainability and bicycle culture. We will be stopping at three parks and setting up a bicycle powered stage for bands. There will be a group ride between each venue, where we&amp;rsquo;ll carry all the equipment to run the event in cargo bikes, trikes and trailers to the next stop. We will even have live music on the ride! &lt;br /&gt;  &lt;br /&gt;  10am Waterfront Park&lt;br /&gt;  3pm Denny Park&lt;br /&gt;  7pm Mural @ Seattle Center&lt;br /&gt; 10pm Secret Location&lt;br /&gt;  &lt;br /&gt;  Stop by the Facebook &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.facebook.com/reqs.php#/pages/Seattle-Bicycle-Music-Festival/107215788359&quot;&gt;page&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://twitter.com/seattlebmf&quot;&gt;twitter&lt;/a&gt; or the &lt;a href=&quot;http://seattlebmf.org/&quot;&gt;website&lt;/a&gt; for additional information. ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[2X', ''),
(1848, 2455067, 2455067, '12:01:00', '14:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'workshop - mobile SMS encryption ', '&lt;img src=&quot;https://we.riseup.net/assets/10438/sms-encrypt-event_large.png&quot; /&gt;&lt;br /&gt; Please join us this Sunday for a workshop on mobile &lt;span&gt;SMS&lt;/span&gt; (text message)&lt;br /&gt; encryption.&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The number of mobile phone users is expected to exceed the 4 billion&lt;br /&gt; mark by the end of this year &amp;ndash; that&amp;rsquo;s more than two thirds of the&lt;br /&gt; world&amp;rsquo;s population. And the number of text messages is expected to reach&lt;br /&gt;  &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.160characters.org&quot;&gt;a whopping 1.8 trillion in 2010&lt;/a&gt;.  From the U.S. to Moldova to Iran to&lt;br /&gt; Uganda cell phones have facilitated all kinds of activism. While mobile&lt;br /&gt; phones bring many benefits to social movements, &lt;a href=&quot;http://mobileactive.org/mobile-surveillance-and-how-avoid-it-new-primer-mobileactive-org&quot;&gt;it is important to be &lt;br /&gt; aware of the digital data trails they leave behind&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;This workshop has two parts:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;First&lt;/em&gt;, a general introduction: why encrypt your &lt;span&gt;SMS&lt;/span&gt;? Oli from CryptoSMS,&lt;br /&gt;  based in Hamburg, will discuss the open-source project&amp;rsquo;s history and&lt;br /&gt; current state.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Second&lt;/em&gt;, you&amp;rsquo;ll have a chance to get your inner hacker on with a hands-on&lt;br /&gt; workshop. We&amp;rsquo;ll install the encryption software on our cell phones,&lt;br /&gt; initialize them, exchange keys, and send encrypted &lt;span&gt;SMS&lt;/span&gt; messages.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Sunday, August 23rd, 12 &amp;ndash; 2 pm (free)&lt;br /&gt; The Garfield Community Center&lt;br /&gt;  2323 East Cherry St., 98122&lt;br /&gt; by the 3, 4, and 48 bus lines&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About CryptoSMS&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt; CryptoSMS.org is a &lt;span&gt;GPL&lt;/span&gt; (general public license) open source application&lt;br /&gt; for cell phones running J2ME (Java for mobiles). It runs on a lot of&lt;br /&gt; phones. CryptoSMS provides public/private key encryption, key generation&lt;br /&gt; and key management. It sends and receives encrypted &lt;span&gt;SMS&lt;/span&gt; and public keys,&lt;br /&gt;  encrypts and de-encrypts files, offers key verification via fingerprints&lt;br /&gt; and provides a secure login.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;CryptoSMS is based on encryption with elliptic curves, which is a modern&lt;br /&gt; solution for encryption with small and/or embedded devices. Elliptic&lt;br /&gt; curve encryption provides good performance and has low memory&lt;br /&gt; requirements. It encrypts only the contents of the messages, but does&lt;br /&gt; not in any way encrypt or scramble the identities of the sender or&lt;br /&gt; recipients. It is not an anonymizer &amp;mdash; it does not hide the device&amp;rsquo;s&lt;br /&gt; id/number from where the &lt;span&gt;SMS&lt;/span&gt; comes and where it goes to.&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://cryptosms.org&quot;&gt;cryptosms.org&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About the presenter&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt; Oli has been involved with the CryptoSMS.org project since its&lt;br /&gt; inception, and mainly keeps the project organized, does the&lt;br /&gt; communication work and strongly enforces the support of many languages&lt;br /&gt; in the CryptoSMS.org user interface. At the moment he is traveling to a&lt;br /&gt; couple of global cities to conduct research on mobile media and&lt;br /&gt; dataveillance, interviewing participants in social movements, hackers&lt;br /&gt; and artists about their use of mobile media. He is based in Hamburg,&lt;br /&gt;  where he suffers from bad weather but enjoys people and culture.&lt;/p&gt; ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[5X', ''),
(1849, 2455088, 2455088, '00:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, '&quot;EAVES OF ASS&quot; ZINE RELEASE READING! ', 'Sunday, &lt;span style=&quot;background:nonetransparentscrollrepeat0%0%;cursor:hand;border-bottom:mediumnone&quot;&gt;September 13&lt;/span&gt;, 7:00 PM @ Pilot Books&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background:nonetransparentscrollrepeat0%0%;cursor:hand;border-bottom:#0066cc1pxdashed&quot;&gt;219 Broadway E., Seattle, WA&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Featuring:&lt;br /&gt;Craven Rock of Eaves of Ass zine&lt;br /&gt;Alexis Wolf of Ilse Content zine&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Craven Rock will read excerpts from Eaves of Ass #7, in which, he reports from the homefront- driving a cab for a yuppie golf tournament when the economy starts to crash and &lt;span&gt;Hurricane Ike&lt;/span&gt; devastates the town, then trying to get into a high-paying drug study. The first in his series Promise &amp; Theft, which looks at the current state of the &lt;span&gt;American Dream&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Olympia&#039;s Alexis Wolf will be reading from her zine Ilse Content, which has been described as having &quot;a child-like wonder of the world that is always profound and reminds us how much amazing stuff we look past everyday.&quot; Alexis has been involved in The Olympia Poetry Collective, SSO Press and is a pioneering member of Use Your Words Press and is a vital part of the Northwest indie lit scene. ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[6X', ''),
