(2092, 2455296, 2455302, '00:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Visual Music ', 'Sensory Cinema 1920s-70 &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;APRIL 9-14, 2010&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; Northwest Film Forum and The Sprocket Society are proud to  present this special series celebrating the history of Visual Music.  Over the past century, there have been a number of prescient artists  who&amp;rsquo;ve approached cinema as a tool for merging visual art and music in  order to create a new synaesthetic art form and explore uncharted areas  of experience. Through a vibrant history of cinematic experiments, these  pioneers have been inventing the concepts, aesthetics, techniques and  technologies on which our modern image-and-sound culture is based.  Visual Music is a rare opportunity to see restored film prints of work  by such master animators as Oskar Fischinger, Mary Ellen Bute, Jordan  Belson and Robert Breer on the big screen. In addition, we&amp;rsquo;ll host a  panel discussion on Seattle&#039;s own history of visual music in the 1960s  and early 70s. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Series website: www.sensorycinema.org&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Curated by Peter Lucas&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Special thanks to the Center For Visual Music, Cindy Keefer,  Cecile Starr, Spencer Sundell and Alex Bush.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;em&gt; &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;This program is made possible by a grant from the National  Endowment For The Arts.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; Full schedule online at: http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/series/1237&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt; ', 7, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
(2093, 2455275, 2455275, '20:30:00', '23:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Community-focused art performance ', '&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:18pt;color:rgb(42,67,227);&quot;&gt;The Temenos Project&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:16pt;&quot;&gt;Proudly Present&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:26pt;color:rgb(185,32,41);font-family:&#039;serif&#039;;&quot;&gt;Herd&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Please join us for the Temenos Project&#039;s fourth shindig and tell all your friends!&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;  &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt; &lt;strong&gt;Date&lt;/strong&gt;: March 19, 2010 &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Time&lt;/strong&gt;: Doors 8:30pm, Starts 9:00pm &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Location&lt;/strong&gt;: &lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.fairegallerycafe.com/&quot;&gt;The Faire Gallery&lt;/a&gt; (1351 East Olive Way) &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cover&lt;/strong&gt;: Donation optional &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;ALL AGES&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s that time again to gather together, to celebrate and wonder at the breadth of beauty our magnificent city has to offer. &lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;This month the Temenos Project is overjoyed to welcome Roberto Ascalon and Crystal Ybarra to the stage.&lt;/p&gt;             &lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;NYC-born Roberto Ascalon is a poet, writer, arts educator, and an integral part of the Seattle spoken-word community. He uses his love for the craft of poetry to transform the societal context that surrounds him. He connects with audiences via universal narratives of a wide topic array, including Spam&amp;hellip; the canned kind.&lt;br /&gt;[&lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://youtube.com/watch?v&quot;&gt;youtube.com/watch?v=WpDlQmM8Lwo&lt;/a&gt;]&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:black;&quot;&gt;Crystal Ybarra brings Seattle words stitched together by hard-won survival. &lt;/span&gt;She is known for the images she creates with her words and doesn&amp;rsquo;t need fancy equipment to show you; her mouth and a microphone do just fine. &lt;span style=&quot;color:black;&quot;&gt;She urges you to go beyond enjoying the show and dares you to experience it instead.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Hope to see you there!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;About the Temenos Project:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The Temenos Project is a performative, philanthropic experiment exploring how to promote high-quality, community-focused arts here in Seattle. We are group of people who believe that artists play vital roles in community and that communities need to find ways to support their artists. This is our attempt to put those things together through a monthly performance series and grant. Think of it as a CSA for artists.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The Temenos Project brings amazing artists together with audiences dedicated to sustaining and celebrating a vibrant arts scene in Seattle. It is a space for performances of all stripes, where artists stand before their community(ies) weaving stories of possibility. Our communities are hungry for visions not only of how the world is, but of how the world might yet be. In order to build a better future we must first see it.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;On the third Friday of every month the Temenos Project will gather to witness, celebrate, and honor two 22-minute performances by this month&amp;rsquo;s winners. Afterwards, 6 artists will have 2-minutes to convince the audience to vote for them for next month&amp;rsquo;s two performance slots (the Try Outs.) The winners will split the grant ($150-300 each) and will have a month to create, refine, dig up a 22-minute performance of their own. On the third Friday of the next month the Temenos Project will do it all again. [temenosproject.org]&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt; ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
