(2196, 2455360, 2455365, '19:00:00', '23:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Bass Ackwards ', '&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.nwfilmforum.org/images/uploaded_images/0000/5226/bassackwards_feature.gif&quot; /&gt; 	 	 	    	 	   	  			 			&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar#&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;   				 	   						  					 					 						 						 						&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1342&quot;&gt;Bass  Ackwards at Northwest Film Forum&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/a&gt; 						 						 						&lt;p&gt;Jun 12 - Jun 17&lt;/p&gt; 						&lt;p&gt;(Linas Phillips, USA, 2010, DigiBeta, 103 min)&lt;/p&gt; 						 						&lt;p&gt; 							 								&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;This is not just another Great American Road Trip movie.  And it&#039;s not an intense journey for self-discovery, or a grand tour to  reveal the true soul of America. This is a travelogue like you&#039;ve not  seen before. It&#039;s the type of film we&amp;rsquo;ve come to love and expect from  Seattle&amp;rsquo;s Linas Phillips. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;Rejected by his girlfriend and given the boot from his friend&#039;s  couch, Linas (a fictional version played by Phillips) is working as a  pooper-scooper and llama feeder and sleeping on the floor at work. When  given an odd-looking 1976 VW bus, he sets out across the country. &lt;em&gt;Bass  Ackwards&lt;/em&gt; premiered at this year&#039;s Sundance, and we&amp;rsquo;re now pleased  to give it the theatrical homecoming it deserves.    &lt;strong&gt;Screens with &lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;Fire Fire I Heard The Cry &lt;/em&gt;&lt;em&gt;(Drew Christie, USA, 2 min)&lt;/em&gt; &lt;br /&gt;An animated documentary about the great Seattle fire. &lt;br /&gt;  							 						 						&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1342&quot;&gt;More&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; ', 6, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
(2197, 2455362, 2455362, '19:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Field Guide to November Days - filmed entirely by bike! ', '&lt;img src=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/images/uploaded_images/0000/5231/fieldguide_feature.gif&quot; /&gt; 	 	 	    	 	   	  			 	   							  						 						 						&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1344&quot;&gt;Field  Guide to November Days at Northwest Film Forum&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/a&gt; 						&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;p&gt;Director in attendance!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; 						 						&lt;p&gt;Jun 14&lt;/p&gt; 						&lt;p&gt;(Nick Peterson, USA, 2010, Beta-SP, 80 min)&lt;/p&gt; 						 						&lt;p&gt; 							 								&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The second feature from Portland filmmaker Nick Peterson (&lt;em&gt;Yellow&lt;/em&gt;), &lt;em&gt;Field  Guide to November Days&lt;/em&gt; was &lt;strong&gt;made entirely with bikes &lt;/strong&gt;instead  of any motorized transport. Everyone working on the film biked to set  and everything (including furniture) was pulled by bike (except for one  trip to the coast!).&lt;/p&gt; 							 						 						&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1344&quot;&gt;More&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
(2198, 2455365, 2455365, '00:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Auto-Morphosis ', '&lt;img src=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/images/uploaded_images/0000/5236/automorph_feature.gif&quot; /&gt; 	 	 	    	 	   	  			 	   						  					 					 						 						 						&lt;a href=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1345&quot;&gt;Auto-Morphosis at Northwest Film Forum&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/a&gt; 						&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;p&gt;Director in attendance!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; 						 						&lt;p&gt;Jun 17&lt;/p&gt; 						&lt;p&gt;(Harrod Blank, USA, 2007, Beta-SP, 76 min)&lt;/p&gt; 						 						&lt;p&gt; 							 								&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Auto-Morphosis&lt;/em&gt; is an inspiring, often hilarious  tour of the world&#039;s wildest art cars and their larger-than-life  creators, who transformed their automobiles into works of mind-bending  art. In this wild-wheeled documentary, director Harrod Blank wows us  with some of the most amazing cars&amp;mdash;and most amazing art&amp;mdash;you&amp;rsquo;ve ever  seen. &lt;/p&gt; 							 						 						&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1345&quot;&gt;More&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
(2199, 2455366, 2455372, '00:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Trash Humpers with Harmony Korine ', '&lt;img src=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/images/uploaded_images/0000/5106/TrashHumpers_feature.jpg&quot; /&gt; 	 	 	    	 	   	  			 	   						  					 					 						 						 						&lt;a href=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1321&quot;&gt;Trash  Humpers at Northwest Film Forum&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/a&gt; 						&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Seattle Premiere&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;p&gt;Director in attendance opening night! &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; 						 						&lt;p&gt;Jun 18 - Jun 24&lt;/p&gt; 						&lt;p&gt;(Harmony Korine, 2009, USA, 35mm, 78 min)&lt;/p&gt; 						 						&lt;p&gt; 							 								&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Enfant terrible Harmony Korine (&lt;em&gt;Gummo,&lt;/em&gt;1997; &lt;em&gt;Julien  Donkey-Boy, &lt;/em&gt;1999) brings an ode to vandalism with his latest  film, &lt;em&gt;Trash Humpers.&lt;/em&gt; The title is to be taken literally: the  protagonists get their kicks by screwing trash cans.  Korine, who plays  one of the leading roles, shows the creative beauty of destruction.  &lt;/p&gt; 							 						 						&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1321&quot;&gt;More&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; ', 7, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
(2200, 2455373, 2455375, '00:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, '9500 Liberty ', '&lt;img src=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/images/uploaded_images/0000/5581/9500_Liberty_l_feature.JPG&quot; /&gt; 	 	 	    	 	   	  			 	   						  					 					 						 						 						&lt;a href=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1425&quot;&gt;9500  Liberty at Northwest Film Forum&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/a&gt; 						 						 						&lt;p&gt;Jun 25 - Jun 27&lt;/p&gt; 						&lt;p&gt;(Eric Byler &amp; Annabel Park, USA, 2009, DigiBeta, 80 min)&lt;/p&gt; 						 						&lt;p&gt; 							 								&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Pre-dating the recent Arizona immigration law by three  years, in 2007 Manassas, Virginia served as the flashpoint of an  exceptionally contentious battle between longtime residents of the  community and the growing population of new residents: immigrants.&lt;/p&gt; 							 						 						&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1425&quot;&gt;More&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; ', 3, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
(2201, 2455377, 2455377, '00:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Bold Native - a film about animal rights ', '&lt;img src=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/images/uploaded_images/0000/5561/BNwebScreens4_feature.jpg&quot; /&gt; 	 	 	    	 	   	  			 	   						  					 					 						 						 						&lt;a href=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1422&quot;&gt;Bold  Native at Northwest Film Forum&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/a&gt; 						 						 						&lt;p&gt;Jun 29&lt;/p&gt; 						&lt;p&gt;(Denis Henry, Hennelly, 2010, USA)&lt;/p&gt; 						 						&lt;p&gt; 							 								From abolitionists to welfarists, Bold Native takes on the issue  of modern animal use and exploitation from several angles within the  context of a road movie adventure story. 							 						&lt;/p&gt; 						&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1422&quot;&gt;More&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
(2202, 2455380, 2455386, '00:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Punishment Park ', '&lt;img src=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/images/uploaded_images/0000/5261/PUNISHMENT-PARK-224_feature.gif&quot; /&gt; 	 	 	    	 	   	  			 	   						  					 					 						 						 						&lt;a href=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1351&quot;&gt;Punishment  Park at Northwest Film Forum&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/a&gt; 						&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;p&gt;New 35mm Print! &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; 						 						&lt;p&gt;Jul 02 - Jul 08&lt;/p&gt; 						&lt;p&gt;(Peter Watkins, USA, 1971, 35mm, 88 min)&lt;/p&gt; 						 						&lt;p&gt; 							 								&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Part dystopian nightmare, part prism through which the  profound tensions  and frustrations in American society in the late  1960s are made  manifest, the film remains a fascinating reflection of a  fractured  America.&lt;/p&gt; 							 						 						&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1351&quot;&gt;More&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; ', 7, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
(2203, 2455400, 2455400, '00:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Karaoke Film Challenge Screenings ', '&lt;img src=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/images/uploaded_images/0000/5521/100509oprah-thumb-500x352-12024_feature.jpg&quot; /&gt; 	 	 	    	 	   	  			 	   						  					 					 						 						 						&lt;a href=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1405&quot;&gt;Karaoke  Film Challenge Screenings at Northwest Film Forum&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/a&gt; 						 						 						&lt;p&gt;Jul 22&lt;/p&gt; 						 						 						&lt;p&gt; 							 								&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Northwest Film Forum and Three Dollar Bill cinema have  once again invited Seattle filmmakers to participate in the Karaoke  Challenge. Ever wonder who&amp;rsquo;s behind those Karaoke videos you sing along  to at the bar on Friday nights? We asked Seattle filmmakers to grab a  camera, pick a song, and become one of them!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Learn how to submit your film here: http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/call-for-entries&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt; 							 						 						&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1405&quot;&gt;More&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
(2204, 2455437, 2455437, '00:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'The 4th Annual BIKE-IN ', '&lt;img src=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/images/uploaded_images/0000/5461/bikein_feature.gif&quot; /&gt; 	 	 	    	 	   	&lt;a href=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1380&quot;&gt;The  4th Annual Seattle Bike-In&lt;/a&gt; 						&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Co-Presented by &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.capitolhillseattle.com/&quot;&gt;CapitolHillSeattle.com&lt;/a&gt; &lt;br /&gt; Sponsored by &lt;a href=&quot;http://kbcs.fm/&quot;&gt;KBCS 91.3FM&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Free!&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;strong /&gt; 						 						&lt;p&gt;Aug 28&lt;/p&gt; 						 						 						&lt;p&gt; 							 								&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Our annual Bike-In is a celebration of green  transportation, our urban  community and summer nights! Grab your bike,  grab your friends&amp;mdash;we&#039;ll see  you for our annual night in Cal Anderson  Park on Capitol Hill!&lt;/p&gt; 							 						 						&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1380&quot;&gt;More&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; ', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[9X', ''),
(2205, 2455422, 2455428, '00:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'The Immaculate Conception of Little Dizzle ', '&lt;img src=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/images/uploaded_images/0000/5366/dizzle_feature.gif&quot; /&gt; 	 	 	    	 	   	  			 	   						  					 					 						 						 						&lt;a href=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1376&quot;&gt;The  Immaculate Conception of Little Dizzle&lt;/a&gt; 						&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Director in attendance!&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Produced with the help of the Film Forum&#039;s &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nwfilmforum.org/live/collection/start-to-finish&quot;&gt;Start-To-Finish&lt;/a&gt;  program &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;strong /&gt; 						 						&lt;p&gt;Aug 13 - Aug 19&lt;/p&gt; 						&lt;p&gt;(David Russo, USA, 2009, DigiBeta, 100 min)&lt;/p&gt; 						 						&lt;p&gt; 							 								&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;David Russo&amp;rsquo;s witty and imaginative film debut explores  key issues of today, including corporate malfeasance, the search for  religion and, of course, male pregnancy. As overheard on a bus at the  Sundance Film Festival, &quot;You &lt;em&gt;have&lt;/em&gt; to see this!&quot; &lt;/p&gt; 							 						 						&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1376&quot;&gt;More&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; ', 7, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
(2206, 2455429, 2455435, '00:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Vincent Moon Retrospective at Northwest Film Forum ', 'Vincent Moon Retrospectivehttp://nwfilmforum.org/live/page/series/1391&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt; 		 		 			 		 	                                               						 	                                 	 		 	  &lt;strong&gt;AUGUST 20-26, 2010&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;Director in attendance!&lt;/strong&gt;   His real name is Mathieu Saura, but it&#039;s under the name of Vincent   Moon that music fans from all over the world know the 30-year-old   filmmaker, who has reinvented the music video as a documentary. After   studying under photographers Michael Ackerman and Antoine D&#039;Agata, the   young music aficionado became increasingly interested in moving images.   The combination of music and film could easily have ended in MTV-land.   But according to Moon, the usual music video has long been stuck in  this  limited marketing world.   Starting in 2006 with his &lt;em&gt;Take Away Shows&lt;/em&gt;, Moon has offered a   non-commercial alternative: small, short films that capture musicians   in the alleys, hallways and elevators of the real world, without   amplifiers or special effects. The &lt;em&gt;Take Away Shows&lt;/em&gt; paved the way   for larger film projects and Moon&#039;s far-reaching résumé, which now   includes concert films and documentaries, all equipped with the special   shadow/light aesthetic that give his images a special abstract quality.   Moon&#039;s greatest strength may be his ability to capture music   without superfluous embellishments. He is a sonic adventurer, constantly   seeking new musical treasure chests. He not only discovers, he   participates, with his camera as an instrument: while in Seattle for   this retrospective Moon will, with a single extended tracking shot,   produce a new one-shot film with local Seattle musicians.   Take a workshop with Vincent Moon: &lt;br /&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nwfilmforum.org/live/page/workshops/85#1416&quot;&gt;Lyrical  Filmmaking: The Art of Documenting Musicians with Vincent  Moon&lt;/a&gt; ', 7, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[3X', ''),
(2207, 2455374, 2455375, '00:00:00', '00:00:00', 'Once', 0, 'Filmmaking Workshop at Northwest Film Forum ', 'Emotionally Sloppy: A Crash-Course in Cinema of the Gut with  Benny and Josh Safdie 		 		 			 		 	                                               			 			 			 			 			 			 					 							 						  			 	                                 	 		 	  &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Visiting Filmmakers!&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; Emotionally Sloppy: A Crash-Course in Cinema of the Gut with Benny  and Josh Safdie Saturday &amp; Sunday, June 26 &amp; 27, 12&amp;ndash;3pm  Instructors: Josh and Benny Safdie Tuition: $35/WigglyWorld members, $40/general  Max Attendance: 12   Visiting filmmakers, Benny and Josh Safdie (&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nwfilmforum.org/live/page/calendar/1348&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Daddy Long  Legs&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;), challenge you to make a story in two days, guided by a  concern for those things most often taken for granted. They will show  clips from their short films and films that inspired them to lead  discussions about process and the intricacies of directing. Despite how  much is taken for granted by the viewer, cinema demands a consideration  for the smallest elements in a scene. Even if it is meant to be  forgotten... it is still felt. On Saturday, you will formulate the seeds  of a story based on ideas that you have felt. Between classes, students  should plan to do some writing which will then be developed further on  Sunday, transforming the ideas into a story that connects with emotions.  With enthusiasm and gumption, students will leave with a story ready to  be filmed. No Time for F-Stops! &lt;br /&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nwfilmforum.org/go/register/workshopform.php?handle&quot;&gt;Register  for Emotionally Sloppy&lt;/a&gt; ', 2, 0, 0, 0, 0, '0[8X', ''),
